ratings.question_text: Overall, how would you rate the workload of this course in comparison to other Yale courses you have taken?
What is your overall assessment of this course?
Do you expect to use this class for credit toward your major, or toward a pre-professional program?

narratives.question_text: How would you summarize ECON 110 05 for a fellow student? Would you recommend ECON 110 05 to another student? Why or why not?
comments: Epic: The Odyssey, The Aeneid, Inferno, Don Quixote, (Heart of Darkness - different for each section/year,) Ulysses; 4 papers; 1 final. Professor Walsh is a great seminar leader, and really kind and cool! If you want to read a ton of good literature, go for it.

This is a terrific class. Take it if you want a great books experience outside of DS. The reading load is huge though, so if you want to finish all the reading, it is a good idea to plan ahead (or take it with other classes that have lighter reading loads). Professor Walsh is great.
Epic is a solid class and all Yale students should be familiar with the works on its syllabus.
Yes. Great class if you don't mind doing a lot of reading.

Lots of boring-ish reading, but Prof. Walsh is great- requirements not too onerous, grading not too harsh. Shop sections of it! Mostly freshmen/sophomores- I took this as a junior and wished I'd taken it earlier because class discussion level was frosh/soph.

Epic was my favorite class of the semester. Yes, it's a lot of work but the reading is definitely manageable. The essays are great because you only have to write 4 out of 6 and they are only 5 or so pages long. Professor Walsh was amazing so if you can take it with him, I would definitely recommend it!

A solid course with a fairly low writing workload, but a fairly high reading workload. I recommend it to anybody with an interest in the history of literature, or a general love for the English language

I really enjoyed this course mainly due to the reading list. I would highly recommend this class to any student who wishes to read the books and who is willing to do a large amount of reading over the course of the semester.
